<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How often should couples have date nights?", answer: "Relationship researchers (including the Gottman Institute and the National Marriage Project) consistently recommend at least one structured date night per week for committed couples. The 2012 'Date Night Opportunity' report from the University of Virginia found that couples who had a weekly date night reported significantly higher communication, romance, and overall satisfaction than couples who didn't. Once or twice a week is the sweet spot — more isn't necessarily better, but less than twice a month correlates with relationship drift." },
  { question: "How much should we spend on a date night?", answer: "There is no right number — it depends entirely on your budget. A typical US date night runs $50–$150 (dinner, drinks, transport, activity), but cheap or free dates work just as well for relationship satisfaction. The key research finding is that the experience matters more than the spending — a $20 picnic in the park can score as high on relationship satisfaction as a $200 fancy restaurant. The calculator helps you set a target, not a minimum." },
  { question: "What counts as a date night?", answer: "Anything that takes you out of routine and gives you focused time together as a couple. It doesn't have to be in the evening, doesn't have to be expensive, and doesn't have to involve dinner. A morning hike, a coffee date, an afternoon museum visit, a cooking class, or even a long walk all count. The two essential ingredients are: just the two of you (no kids, no friends), and intentional time set aside for the relationship." },
  { question: "How do parents fit in date nights?", answer: "Three approaches work well. First, schedule a recurring slot (e.g., every Friday at 7pm) and treat it as protected time. Second, line up a babysitter rotation with another couple — you watch their kids one Saturday, they watch yours the next. Third, do at-home date nights once kids are in bed: cook together, watch a movie, play a game, or just talk without screens. Quality matters more than location." },
  { question: "Can date night save a struggling relationship?", answer: "On its own, no — but date nights are correlated with better communication, more sex, and lower divorce rates, which are all things struggling relationships need. The University of Virginia study found that couples who started weekly date nights reported improvements within 3 months. If your relationship is genuinely in crisis, date night is a nice supplement to therapy, not a substitute for it." }
]) %>

